abstract.value: George Marion (1905-1955) was a journalist, author, and Communist Party activist. In 1936, Marion went to Spain to cover the Spanish Civil War for the <title render="italic">Daily Worker</title>and the <title render="italic">New Masses</title>. The images in this collection were accrued by Marion in the course of his work as a journalist in Spain. The collection contains group photographs and portraits of members of the Abraham Lincoln Brigade, Republican military leaders, Communist Party leaders, military vehicles, political demonstrations/rallies, Spanish munitions workers, and street scenes.

p.value: Materials are open to researchers. Please contact the Tamiment Library & Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives for more information and to schedule an appointment, tamiment.wagner@nyu.edu or 212-998-2630.

Published citations should take the following form: <lb/><lb/>Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library <lb/>70 Washington Square South <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

Marion accrued the images in this collection during his tenure as a correspondent for the <title render="italic">Daily Worker</title>and the <title render="italic">New Masses</title>. The majority of the images were procured by Marion from the photographic bureau, Photo Mayo, Madrid. Two photographs are credited to D. Kraman. The images in the Marion Photograph Collection were separated from Marion’s manuscript materials in the course of processing.

The photographic prints are identified by four numbers separated by colons. The first number refers to the collection number, the second to the box number, the third to the folder number, and the fourth to the individual print. For example, the first print in this collection is labeled 45:1:1:1. Negatives are numbered in the same fashion and if there is a matching print, the print number is listed below the negative number.
